      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">A 30-year-old patient undergoing a kidney function evaluation is curious about the characteristics of cortical nephrons. The healthcare provider explains the key features of cortical nephrons and distinguishes them from juxtamedullary nephrons. All of the following are the features of cortical nephrons, except?</span></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q9774687",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33819,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        2
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ans. B) Long Loop of Henle</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option B:&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Cortical nephrons have a <strong>short loop of Henle</strong>, which means that the <strong>descending</strong> and <strong>ascending limbs</strong> of the loop of Henle <strong>do not extend</strong> <strong>deeply</strong> into the renal medulla. In contrast, <strong>juxtamedullary nephrons</strong> have a <strong>long loop of Henle</strong> that extends <strong>deep</strong> into the <strong>medulla</strong> and is <strong>essential</strong> for <strong>concentrating urine</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Explanation:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">All other options are the <strong>correct statements</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option A.&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Cortical nephrons, like all nephrons, are involved in <strong>both filtration</strong> and <strong>reabsorption processes</strong>. <strong>Filtration</strong> occurs in the <strong>renal corpuscle</strong> (<strong>glomerulus</strong> and <strong>Bowman&#39;s capsule</strong>). Reabsorption occurs as the <strong>filtrate</strong> passes through the <strong>renal tubules</strong>, with essential substances being <strong>reabsorbed</strong> into the <strong>bloodstream</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option C.&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">While <strong>vasa recta</strong> are more <strong>prominent</strong> in <strong>juxtamedullary nephrons</strong>, <strong>cortical nephrons</strong> also have associated <strong>peritubular capillaries</strong>, which are <strong>essential</strong> for the <strong>exchange</strong> of <strong>substances</strong> (reabsorption and secretion) <strong>between</strong> the <strong>blood</strong> and the <strong>renal tubules</strong>. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option D.&nbsp;</span></span></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Cortical nephrons</span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"> have well-developed <strong>peritubular capillaries</strong>, which are an <strong>integral part</strong> of their <strong>structure</strong>. Peritubular capillaries surround the <strong>renal tubules</strong> and are involved in the <strong>exchange</strong> of <strong>substances</strong> with the <strong>renal tubular cells</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">To assess <strong>knowledge</strong> of the <strong>distinctive features</strong> of <strong>cortical nephrons</strong>, emphasizing their <strong>anatomical</strong> and <strong>functional characteristics</strong>, and <strong>differentiate</strong> them from <strong>juxtamedullary nephrons</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ref</span></span></span></u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology, 2<sup>nd</sup> South Asia edition, pg no: 486</span></span></span></strong></p>",
