      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ans. D) Both A and B</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Explanation:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Urea Transporter UT A1 and UT-A3 </span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">are regulated by<strong> Vasopressin UT-G </strong></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">UT-A1</span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"> and <strong>UT-A3</strong> are both regulated by <strong>vasopressin</strong>. Vasopressin stimulates these urea <strong>transporters</strong> to <strong>reabsorb urea</strong> from the <strong>urine</strong>, <strong>aiding</strong> in the <strong>concentration</strong> of <strong>urine</strong>.</span></span></span></span><br />\r\n\t&nbsp;</li>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">UT-G is <strong>not regulated by vasopressin</strong>. UT-G is a <strong>urea transporter</strong> that <strong>primarily functions</strong> in the <strong>gastrointestinal tract</strong> rather than the <strong>kidneys</strong> and is not directly influenced by vasopressin in the context of <strong>renal water</strong> and <strong>solute regulation</strong></span></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">To assess <strong>knowledge</strong> of <strong>how vasopressin</strong> regulates <strong>specific urea transporters</strong> (<strong>UT-A1</strong> and <strong>UT-A3</strong>) in the <strong>renal tubules</strong> and their role in <strong>concentrating urine</strong>, particularly in the <strong>context</strong> of <strong>diabetes insipidus</strong> treatment.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ref</span></span></span></u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">: Ganong&#39;s Review of Medical physiology, 25<sup>th</sup> edition, pg no: 686</span></span></span></strong></span></span></span></span></p>",
