        2
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ans. C) Juxtamedullary Nephrons</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option </span></span></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">C:&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Juxtamedullary nephrons are mainly involved in <strong>creating</strong> and <strong>maintaining osmotic gradients</strong> in the <strong>kidneys</strong>. These nephrons have <strong>long loops of Henle</strong> that <strong>extend deep</strong> into the <strong>renal medulla</strong>. The <strong>long loops</strong>, particularly the <strong>descending limbs</strong> and <strong>ascending limbs</strong>, are responsible for <strong>establishing</strong> and <strong>maintaining</strong> the <strong>concentration gradient</strong> in the <strong>medullary interstitium</strong>. This gradient is <strong>essential</strong> for the <strong>kidney&#39;s ability</strong> to <strong>concentrate</strong> or <strong>dilute urine</strong>, depending on the <strong>body&#39;s hydration needs</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Explanation:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option A.&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">The juxtaglomerular apparatus plays a role in <strong>regulating blood pressure</strong> and <strong>glomerular filtration rate</strong> but is not primarily responsible for creating osmotic gradients in the kidneys.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option B.&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Cortical nephrons have <strong>shorter loops of Henle</strong> and are not as involved in establishing the medullary concentration gradient as juxtamedullary nephrons.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option D.&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Glomerular capillaries are involved in the <strong>initial filtration</strong> of <strong>blood</strong> to <strong>form</strong> the <strong>primary filtrate</strong>, but they are not primarily responsible for creating osmotic gradients in the kidney.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">To <strong>evaluate knowledge</strong> of the <strong>nephron types</strong> and <strong>structures</strong> that are <strong>primarily</strong> involved in <strong>creating</strong> and <strong>maintaining osmotic gradients</strong> in the <strong>kidneys</strong>, with a <strong>focus</strong> on <strong>juxtamedullary nephrons</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ref</span></span></span></u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology, 2<sup>nd</sup> South Asia edition, pg no: 486</span></span></span></strong></p>",
