      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ans. C) Increased Effective Osmotic Pressure &ndash; Decreased ADH Secretion</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option C:&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">An <strong>increase</strong> in <strong>effective osmotic pressure</strong> in the <strong>blood</strong>, often <strong>caused</strong> by <strong>high solute concentration</strong> (e.g., due to <strong>dehydration</strong> or <strong>high salt intake</strong>), it <strong>signals</strong> the <strong>body</strong> to <strong>increase ADH secretion</strong>. <strong>Increased ADH</strong> levels <strong>promote</strong> water <strong>reabsorption</strong> helping to <strong>lower blood osmolarity</strong></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/01/22/picture10.jpg\" style=\"height:495px; width:1000px\" /></strong></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Explanation:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong>Option A.</strong>&nbsp;</span></span><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong>Correctly matched</strong>. Alcohol consumption <strong>inhibits</strong> the <strong>release</strong> of <strong>antidiuretic hormone</strong> (ADH), also known as <strong>vasopressin</strong>, from the <strong>posterior pituitary gland</strong>. As a result, <strong>decreased ADH secretion</strong> leads to <strong>reduced water reabsorption</strong> in the <strong>kidneys</strong>, causing <strong>increased urine production</strong>. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option B. Correctly matched</span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">. When the <strong>ECF volume decreases</strong>, for example due to <strong>dehydration</strong>, <strong>bleeding</strong>, or <strong>loss</strong> of body fluids, the body responds by <strong>increasing ADH secretion</strong> to <strong>conserve water</strong> by <strong>enhancing</strong> the <strong>reabsorption </strong>of <strong>water</strong> in the kidneys, <strong>reducing urine production</strong>, and <strong>maintain blood pressure</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option D. Correctly matched</span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">. <strong>Vomiting</strong> typically <strong>leads</strong> to a <strong>loss</strong> of <strong>body fluids</strong>, causing <strong>dehydration</strong>. In response to <strong>dehydration</strong> and <strong>reduced blood volume</strong>, the body usually <strong>increases ADH secretion</strong> to <strong>conserve water</strong>. <strong>Increased ADH levels</strong> promote <strong>water reabsorption</strong> in the <strong>kidneys</strong> and <strong>reduce urine output</strong> to <strong>help maintain fluid</strong> <strong>balance</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">To test understanding of the <strong>effects</strong> of <strong>alcohol</strong> on <strong>ADH secretion</strong> and how <strong>decreased ECF volume</strong> and <strong>vomiting</strong> can lead to <strong>increased ADH</strong> <strong>secretion</strong> as part of the <strong>body&#39;s response</strong> to <strong>maintain fluid balance</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ref</span></span></span></u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">: Ganong&rsquo;s Review of Medical physiology, 25<sup>th</sup> edition, pg no: 696</span></span></span></strong></p>",
