      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">You are a Medical Practitioner working in a Primary Care Clinic. A 32-year-old patient named Emily visits your clinic with concerns about recent symptoms. She reports experiencing increased thirst and more frequent Urination over the last few weeks. Emily has no known history of Diabetes or Kidney Disease and generally maintains a Healthy Lifestyle. What will be Renal Threshold value of Glucose in the Kidneys?</span></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q2032929",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33825,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        2
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ans. C) 180 mg%</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Explanation:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">The <strong>Renal threshold</strong> for <strong>Glucose Reabsorption</strong> in the <strong>Kidneys</strong> is typically <strong>around 180 milligrams per deciliter (mg/dL)</strong> or <strong>10 millimoles per liter (mmol/L)</strong> of <strong>Blood</strong>.</span></span></span></span><br />\r\n\t&nbsp;</li>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">This means that under <strong>Normal Physiological Conditions</strong>, the <strong>Renal Tubules</strong> will <strong>efficiently reabsorb Glucose</strong> from the <strong>Glomerular Filtrate</strong>, and Glucose will not appear in the Urine until Blood Glucose levels exceed this threshold.</span></span></span></span><br />\r\n\t&nbsp;</li>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">When <strong>Blood Glucose Levels</strong> rise <strong>above 180 mg/dL</strong>, the Renal Tubules may not be able to <strong>reabsorb</strong> all the <strong>filtered Glucose</strong>, leading to <strong>Glycosuria</strong> (the <strong>presence</strong> of <strong>Glucose</strong> in the <strong>Urine</strong>). This threshold can vary <strong>among individuals</strong> and can <strong>change</strong> <strong>under different Physiological conditions.</strong></span></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Understanding the Renal Threshold of Glycosuria. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ref</span></span></u></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">: Ganong&#39;s Review of Medical physiology, 25<sup>th</sup> edition, pg no: 680</span></span></strong></span></span></p>",
