        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">During a nephrology conference, healthcare professionals are discussing the role of epithelial cells in the collecting ducts and their association with acid secretion. Which of the following epithelial cell types in the collecting ducts is primarily responsible for acid secretion and contributes to maintaining proper pH balance in the body?</span></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q9645157",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33822,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        2
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ans. C) I Cells</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option C:&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Intercalated cells (I cells) are <strong>specialized cells</strong> found in the <strong>collecting ducts</strong> of the <strong>nephrons</strong>. They are <strong>primarily responsible</strong> for the <strong>secretion</strong> of <strong>H+ ions</strong> and <strong>K+ reabsorption</strong> and not for Na+ reabsorption. These cells <strong>play</strong> a <strong>role</strong> in <strong>acid-base regulation</strong> and secrete <strong>protons (H+)</strong> into the <strong>urine</strong> to help <strong>maintain</strong> proper <strong>pH balance</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Explanation:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option A.&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Principal cells (P cells) are found in the <strong>collecting ducts</strong> and also in <strong>DCT</strong>. They are <strong>primarily responsible</strong> for the <strong>reabsorption</strong> of <strong>sodium</strong> and the <strong>secretion</strong> of <strong>potassium</strong> via <strong>Epithelial Na+ channels</strong> and <strong>renal outer medullary K+ channels</strong> respectively. They play a <strong>central role</strong> in <strong>adjusting sodium</strong> and <strong>potassium levels</strong> in response to <strong>aldosterone</strong>. When <strong>aldosterone</strong> is present, principal cells <strong>increase sodium reabsorption</strong> and <strong>potassium secretion</strong>, contributing to <strong>sodium</strong> and <strong>water retention</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:48px\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Option B &amp; D.&nbsp;</span></span></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">G cells</span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"> and <strong>L cells</strong> are found in the <strong>gastrointestinal tract</strong> and involved in the <strong>digestion</strong> and <strong>nutrient absorption</strong>. They are not associated with acid secretion in the collecting ducts. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Evaluate the healthcare team&#39;s <strong>knowledge</strong> of the <strong>specific epithelial cell type</strong> in the <strong>collecting ducts</strong> responsible for <strong>acid secretion</strong> and its <strong>role</strong> in <strong>acid-base regulation</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ref</span></span></span></u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">:&nbsp; Ganong&rsquo;s Review of Medical physiology, 25<sup>th</sup> edition, pg no: 672</span></span></span></strong> </span></span></span></span></p>",
