      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">A 55-year-old patient with chronic kidney disease presents with metabolic acidosis. The healthcare team is discussing the potential sites of bicarbonate reabsorption in the renal tubules as part of the diagnostic workup. What percentage of bicarbonate reabsorption primarily occurs in the proximal convoluted tubules, and how does this relate to the patient&#39;s metabolic acidosis</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q3766965",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33824,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        2
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ans. D) 80-90%</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Explanation:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">In the <strong>Renal Tubules</strong>, the <strong>Bicarbonate Reabsorption</strong> will take place in almost all the parts <strong>except descending</strong> and <strong>ascending</strong> <strong>thin limbs</strong> of the <strong>Henle&rsquo;s loop</strong></span></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Majority&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">of the <strong>bicarbonate reabsorption</strong> (<strong>around 80 &ndash; 90%</strong>) will take place in the <strong>proximal tubules</strong></span></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">In the <strong>thick ascending limb loop</strong> of <strong>Henle</strong>, around <strong>10%</strong> of the <strong>filtered bicarbonate</strong> will be <strong>reabsorbed</strong> and the <strong>remaining bicarbonate reabsorption</strong> takes place in the <strong>distal tubules</strong> and <strong>collecting ducts</strong></span></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:#374151\">Educational Objective</span></span></u></strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:#374151\">:</span></span></u></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:#374151\">Assess the <strong>understanding</strong> of the <strong>major site</strong> of <strong>bicarbonate reabsorption</strong> in the <strong>nephron</strong>, and its <strong>relevance</strong> to <strong>metabolic acidosis</strong> in <strong>patients</strong> with <strong>renal dysfunction</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">Ref</span></span></span></u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:black\">: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology, 2<sup>nd</sup> South Asia edition, pg no: 537</span></span></span></strong></span></span></span></span></p>",
